~ librarian_mycologist_fate
Iris Bookwright: [#mysterious] Dr. Spore? He was last seen wandering into the woods, muttering about underground libraries. \n\n[#conspiratorial] Local farmers say that wherever he walks now, the most perfect mushrooms sprout.\n\nThe mycorrhizal network has its own librarians, apparently.
- "Can we see the rare books now?" => librarian_viewing_rare_books
- "Ask about something else" => librarian_main_menu

~ librarian_browse
Iris Bookwright: [#cheerful] By all means! The library loves curious browsers. \n\nJust remember - some books in the herbarium section prefer to remain... private.
Iris Bookwright: [#warning] If you hear whispers coming from the field guides, it's best to move along quickly.
- "Ask about something else" => librarian_main_menu
- "Thanks for the advice" => END

~ librarian_general_help
Iris Bookwright: [#helpful] Back for more knowledge? The books have missed you.\n\n [#observant] Your aura suggests you need something about... water systems?
- "How did you know?" => librarian_aura_reading
- "Actually, I need help with..." => librarian_specific_help
- "Just visiting" => librarian_social_visit

~ librarian_aura_reading
Iris Bookwright: [#knowing] Dear, when you work with living books for long enough, you develop certain... sensitivities.\n\nThe library books recognize fellow seekers of knowledge.
Iris Bookwright: [#practical] Plus, you have a slight leafy smell. Definitely been in the wetlands section.
=> librarian_specific_help

~ librarian_specific_help
Iris Bookwright: [#attentive] What knowledge do you seek today?
- "Water ecology" => librarian_water_ecology
- "Rare species" => librarian_rare_species
- "Old campus history" => librarian_campus_history
- "Actually, let me ask about something else" => librarian_main_menu

~ librarian_water_ecology
Iris Bookwright: [#enthusiastic] Water ecology! Our aquatic texts are particularly lively. \n\nActually, Dr. River Stone just returned a fascinating study on riparian systems.
Iris Bookwright: [#warning] Be careful with "Ripples Through Time" - the pages literally flow like water during full moons.
if 0>1:
	do QuestSystem.add_item("aquatic_book", "A book that leaves your hands slightly damp")
=> librarian_water_warning

~ librarian_ancient_books
Iris Bookwright: [#reverent] Indeed they are! You can feel the weight of time in these pages.
Iris Bookwright: [#educational] Some are bound in vellum - that's treated animal skin. Much more durable than paper.\n\nThese particular volumes contain observations of species long before modern taxonomy existed.
- "What's inside them?" => librarian_ancient_contents
- "Can I still not touch them?" => librarian_handling_books
- "Maybe show me something else?" => librarian_main_menu

~ librarian_ancient_contents
Iris Bookwright: [#excited] Oh, wonderful descriptions! Early naturalists had such poetic language.\n\nThere's a 1723 description of moss sporophytes as "tiny sentinels wearing soldier's caps."
Iris Bookwright: [#amused] And lichens were often called "poverty plants" because they could grow on bare rock.
=> librarian_viewing_rare_books

~ librarian_handling_books
Iris Bookwright: [#apologetic] I wish you could! But these volumes are quite fragile. \n\n[#practical] The oils from our hands accelerate deterioration. Even cotton gloves leave fibers.
Iris Bookwright: The best I can offer is viewing under my supervision - I'll turn the pages for you.
=> librarian_viewing_rare_books

~ librarian_viewing_rare_books
Iris Bookwright: [#helpful] I can prepare a viewing session during library hours.\n\n[#instructive] White gloves provided. No note-taking with regular pens - pencil only.\n\n[#conspiratorial] Some pages still smell of pine tar and wood smoke from 1800s preservation methods.
do QuestSystem.add_quest("arrange_rare_book_viewing")
- "I'd love to set up a viewing" => librarian_appointment_setup
- "What other rare books do you have?" => librarian_rare_species
- "Maybe another time" => librarian_main_menu

~ librarian_appointment_setup
Iris Bookwright: [#pleased] Excellent! I'll need 48 hours notice to prepare the materials.\n\nThe manuscripts prefer time to acclimate to visitors.
Iris Bookwright: [#practical] Fill out the request form at the desk. Specify which texts you'd like to examine.
do QuestSystem.add_item("rare_books_request_form")
=> librarian_main_menu

~ librarian_water_warning
Iris Bookwright: [#serious] One warning about aquatic literature...\n\nNever, ever read underwater texts during a thunderstorm.
Iris Bookwright: [#mysterious] The last student who tried reported seeing every raindrop that ever fell simultaneously.
- "I'll be careful" => librarian_main_menu
- "That's... terrifying and beautiful" => librarian_profound_response
- "I need that book for research" => END

~ librarian_profound_response
Iris Bookwright: [#impressed] You grasp the duality! Most people only see the warning, not the wonder.
Iris Bookwright: [#thoughtful] Perhaps when you're more experienced, I'll show you my collection of storm-responsive texts.
do relationship_level += 1
=> librarian_main_menu

~ librarian_rare_species
Iris Bookwright: [#knowledgeable] We have extensive documentation on endangered species!\n\n[#concerned] Some of which no longer exist. Their last descriptions are preserved here.\n\n [#hopeful] Though occasionally, students discover "extinct" species still surviving in hidden places.
- "Like what?" => librarian_lost_species_examples
- "That's sad but hopeful" => librarian_conservation_role
- "Ask about something else" => librarian_main_menu

~ librarian_lost_species_examples
Iris Bookwright: [#storytelling] The Adirondack Velvet Moss - thought extinct for 80 years!\n\n A graduate student found it in 2019, growing on a single boulder.\n\n [#whimsical] It had been hiding, waiting for someone to look in the right place.
=> librarian_conservation_role

~ librarian_conservation_role
Iris Bookwright: [#passionate] This is why libraries matter! We preserve knowledge of what was, so future generations can restore what is lost.\n\nEvery extinct species we document could hold keys to ecological recovery.\n\n[#encouraging] Perhaps you'll be the one to find something everyone thinks is lost forever.
=> librarian_main_menu

~ librarian_campus_history
Iris Bookwright: [#nostalgic] The college archives! A treasure trove of academic evolution.\n\nFrom its founding in 1911 to today, every major environmental movement has left its mark here.
Iris Bookwright: [#interesting] We have the original blueprints for the building's sustainable design. It was revolutionary for its time!
- "Tell me more about early sustainability" => librarian_early_green_building
- "Any interesting stories?" => librarian_campus_legends
- "Where can I find these archives?" => librarian_archive_location

~ librarian_early_green_building
Iris Bookwright: [#educational] This building was one of the first with passive solar design in 1911!\n\nThe architects oriented it to maximize natural light and minimize heating needs.
Iris Bookwright: [#proud] They even planned the landscape to work with seasonal winds. Ahead of their time!
=> librarian_archive_location

~ librarian_campus_legends
Iris Bookwright: [#amused] Oh, there are stories! Like the time in 1965 when students protested by planting guerilla gardens.\n\nThe dean came to campus one morning to find native wildflowers in every parking space.
Iris Bookwright: [#pleased] They couldn't remove them - it was protected native habitat. That's how we got our current green spaces!
=> librarian_archive_location

~ librarian_archive_location
Iris Bookwright: [#helpful] The campus archives are in Special Collections, second floor.\n\nYearbooks, faculty records, construction documents - it's all preserved up there.\n\n[#encouraging] The old photographs are fascinating. You can see how the landscape has changed - or hasn't!
=> librarian_main_menu

~ librarian_social_visit
Iris Bookwright: [#pleased] Social visits are the best! The books appreciate company.\n\nWould you like some mycological tea? I brew it myself.\n\nIt's entirely safe, despite what Professor Moss says about the "minor consciousness expansion effects."
- "Yes, please!" => librarian_tea_time
- "Maybe later" => librarian_decline_tea

~ librarian_tea_time
Iris Bookwright: [#delighted] Wonderful! Let me steep a fresh pot...\n\n[#chatty] You know, I've been experimenting with adding adaptogenic mushrooms.\n\nThe reading comprehension boost is remarkable, though it does make the books more chatty.
do relationship_level += 1
do QuestSystem.add_buff("enhanced_reading", 60)
=> librarian_tea_effects

~ librarian_tea_effects
Iris Bookwright: [#observant] How do you feel? Any enhanced bibliophilic tendencies?\n\nSome people report their reading speed doubling, but books occasionally read back. [wait=1]\n\n[#reassuring] It wears off in about an hour. Usually.
- "It's quite pleasant!" => librarian_main_menu
- "The words are... shimmering" => librarian_tea_concerns
- "I should go study while I can" => END

~ librarian_tea_concerns
Iris Bookwright: [#concerned] Shimmering? Interesting! That usually only happens with advanced readers.\n\n[#practical] If the books start asking personal questions, just compliment their binding. They like that.
=> librarian_main_menu

~ librarian_decline_tea
Iris Bookwright: [#understanding] Of course! Not everyone's ready for enhanced bibliographic perception.
Iris Bookwright: [#mysterious] Though the offer stands. The fungi remember patience.
=> librarian_main_menu